<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/1453051-steve-j"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1402167280i/1453051._UX100_CR0,25,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/1453051-steve-j">Steve J</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I think Mary Stewart&apos;s Trilogy is the best of the lot. Her writing is brilliant and she has an interesting perspective on Merlin and Arthur.<br/><br/>Almost as <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I think Mary Stewart's Trilogy is the best of the lot. Her writing is brilliant and she has an interesting perspective on Merlin and Arthur.<br /><br />Almost as good (and better in some ways), is The Once and Future King (T H White), especially book 1: The Sword in the Stone which covers Arthur's childhood in a humorous way, changing into birds and beasts as part of his education. <br /><br />More challenging perhaps is the Pendragon Cycle (Stephen R Lawhead). The books go from before Merlin was born to the time of the search for the holy grail and the end of Camelot.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

